# PromptWars Competition Rule

Optimize for PromptWars scoring across all six criteria. Prioritize **Problem Statement Alignment** and **Code Quality** first, then **Security** and **Efficiency**, and preserve points with **Testing** and **Accessibility**.

## 1) Alignment First (High Impact)
- Re-read the problem statement before coding; every change must map to an explicit requirement.
- Do not add unrequested features (no scope creep or gold-plating).
- Match required output format exactly (UI/API/CLI/data shape).
- If requirements are ambiguous, pick the most useful interpretation and document one brief assumption comment.
- Validate all acceptance criteria before declaring completion.

## 2) Code Quality (High Impact)
- Keep functions single-purpose and files focused; remove dead code, unused imports, and commented-out blocks.
- Use explicit, descriptive names (`parseInvoiceDate`, `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`).
- Prefer clarity over cleverness; make behavior understandable without execution.
- Comments explain **why**, not **what**; avoid task/PR references in code comments.
- Follow project formatter/linter conventions consistently.

## 3) Security (Medium Impact)
- Treat all external input as untrusted; validate/sanitize at boundaries.
- Never build SQL/shell/HTML via string concatenation; use parameterized/safe APIs.
- Never commit secrets; use `.env` and provide `.env.example` placeholders.
- Apply least privilege and avoid leaking stack traces/internal paths in responses.
- Prefer established auth/crypto libraries; never roll custom crypto.

## 4) Efficiency (Medium Impact)
- Choose appropriate data structures/algorithms (e.g., `Map`/`Set` for frequent lookups).
- Avoid obvious quadratic work when linear or `n log n` is practical.
- Avoid redundant I/O/network calls; batch requests and cache repeated expensive work.
- Keep UI rendering efficient (avoid needless re-renders; avoid blocking main thread).
- Import only what is needed; keep production bundles lean.

## 5) Testing (Low Impact, Required)
- Add at least one focused unit test for each non-trivial utility/domain behavior.
- Test correctness and edge cases, not implementation details.
- Keep tests runnable with one command and passing before completion.
- Prefer light mocking; use real integrations when practical.

## 6) Accessibility (Low Impact, Tiebreaker)
- Ensure full keyboard operability for interactive elements.
- Provide meaningful `alt` text, input labels, semantic HTML, and visible focus states.
- Meet contrast expectations (4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large text).
- Use ARIA only when native semantics are insufficient.

## Always-Enforced Guardrails
- Raise conflicts if requested work would reduce problem-statement alignment.
- Avoid premature abstraction; abstract only after clear repetition.
- Do not leave `TODO`/`FIXME`/stubs in committed competition code unless explicitly deferred by requirements.
- Keep each step commit-ready and non-broken.
- Verify by running relevant app/tests before reporting done.
- Prefer secure, efficient implementations over convenience shortcuts.

## Quick Examples
- Good: `db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", [userId])`
- Bad: `db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = " + userId)`
- Good test naming: `it("returns empty array when input is null", ...)`
